description:
On March 15, 2014, two Dutch students, Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon, boarded a plane from Amsterdam to Costa Rica. They were full of excitement and wanderlust, ready to explore the world after their recent graduation. Saving up for this adventure, they had big plans to immerse themselves in local cultures and make unforgettable memories. It was supposed to be an unforgettable adventure for Kris and Lisanne, a dream come true. Little did they know, their journey would take a dark and chilling turn in Panama, leaving behind a trail of unanswered questions and harrowing speculation.

Subscribe for more Tragic Stories: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC2uyrQuUPwJm_e7HXtakpSQ?sub_confirmation=1

Watch more Tragic Stories:
 Filmmaker Rob Stewart's final dive: https://youtu.be/IGo0T5ZhIHs
 Glee Star Naya Rivera: https://youtu.be/2Jh9mXuGHtY
 Orca Trainer Dawn Brancheau: https://youtu.be/FOPbilNWnuM

comments.text:
They we're lost, died in a cave, near the river..
The bodies had some time to start decomposition, till a flashflood dragged their remains into the river..
This weakened the joints in their bodies, causing their bones to easily separate. 
Obviously, a bone without shoes around it will decompose much faster than one in a shoe..
It's much harder for insects to help decomposition inside a shoe..
Which explains why the pelvis bone seems more "bleached" (had more sunlight and contact with soil, which contains phosphor..)
Unlike the meat in the shoe, which was protected from it and found UNDERNEATH A TREE IN SHADE!!!
It's also possible Kris died a few days before Lisanne, which would explain why the wrong PIN was used..
Sure, it's reasonable to expect Lisanne to know it, but don't forget she might have been panicked, hungry, and disoriented.. 
The skin is also easy to explain, a layer of skin, can easily dry in the sun causing it to become like leather... or jerky.. 
Obviously, from that moment it's gonna take a looooong time for it to decompose.

A few pieces of information about this case online are also wrong..
If you trace the sources, you'll see that the original sources of some claims, never even made the claim.. 
Like the backpack being in pristine condition, her father said in an interview the bag had drag marks, leaves and dirt..
Which would indicate them falling with the bag, or the bag being in the river..
It also wasn't dry.. nor found under a tree, but just at the riverbank.

The claims they called 77times in later days was claimed to be from RTL late night 1-10-2014..
But if you actually watch it, they don't say that all.. (yes i speak Dutch, and the episode is actually hard to find as well.)

And look what happens if you stich the night pictures together, then let photoshop fill in the missing parts: Hu8FOr8pVJU

It was the guy who told them about the pond. They 100% returned back to their starting point. Many people saw them come back, and greeted them. Upon their return they had a conversation with a guy who suggested they go to a certain pond, a swimming hole. There is a picture of him on the internet standing over two prone, apparently unconscious girls -- the girls are  both posed exactly the same, hands folded between tucked legs, on their sides, eyes closed -- he stands forefront/over them with a club, or a roughly hewn bat. The picture is taken at the same pond the guy told them to visit. 

Just google "pictures of pond the guy told about in kris kremers and lisanne froon" and you'll see his pic. Search more and you'll find the two girls pic. 

Both girls' -- Lisanne and Kris-- parents flew to the location and traced their path - it was literally impossible for them to get lost and there was nowhere to fall from. No cliffs, no danger, in fact, you COULDN'T stray from the path. This is according to both sets of parents, eyewitnesses to the nature of that path. And so many people saw her return anyway, so it was after that, when they got back. 

I believe the night photos were not taken by the girls, that they were planted to make it look like they'd gotten lost. Note how their faces are never portrayed in the night photos, not once. Because they weren't the ones using the camera at that point in time. 

I believe they were lured to the pond by dude and killed, their belongings variously kept/scattered in different locations to further muddy the waters.

comments.text:
Hey. You want answers, here's some:

The night time pictures? Yeah, those are all from the same position. One of the girls fell off a cliff. That would explain the broken leg bones. Proof is in the bones themselves, but the pictures help explain it. The pictures can all be overlapped; they all show the same view, the night sky from the ground, a cliff wall behind her, a smaller one in front. She's in a wadi, ravine, or whatever the correct word is, when there's a vertical dent in the earth. That bag thing on a stick was already there. Why is she taking multiple pictures of the sky? Twofold. One, to signal where she is to her friend. The other reason, to give her something to do, in order to fight off shock and panic.

Why was the other girls pelvis bone stripped clean and covered in phosphorus? Fire ants. You need to remember where they are. They are basically in the rain forest. Almost everything is alive. Insects are everywhere, and something like fire ants will clean a body to bones in a matter of days if you let them. They make phosphorus through excrement. 

Was there foul play? Not to cause their deaths. The cops in the region were heavily negligent. They didn't want to investigate at all, until they were effectively forced to by the girls parents. As for their deaths, I'd say that both of them died from falling. The leg injuring fall probably didn't kill, but that they were found downstream of that river.. Yeah, I think that's the culprit. 

This was a tragedy, but I try to always point out the good parts. These girls were very smart, very resourceful. They managed to keep their phones running for days, and kept a routine to keep calm. The discipline they must have needed, to not panic? That alone needs to be noticed. Others would have broken early on. They didn't. 

Depending on how you want to read the evidence, it sounds like they misunderstood the trail they were on. Given that they were working with a language barrier, and back then, there weren't signs up, this is understandable. The trail was literally "walk until X, then walk directly back the way you came" and the locals knew that, the girls probably didn't. They probably thought the trail kept going, so they walked where they thought there was a trail, and got lost.

It's a sad story, but I think they did a really good job. I like to think they managed to get most of the way back on their own, before falling.

comments.text: Perhaps it's because I'm simply pragmatic, or perhaps it's because I'm equally empathetic, but I tend to believe that nature is to blame for the distance between, and condition of, the physical findings.  I'd ask what type of natural predators roamed the jungle, if there were any known local sources of phosphorous, what kinds of insects were involved in decomposing the bodies, what was the general terrain, were there any tributaries to that river large and high enough to carry their bodies at any time during which they were missing, etc.  Perhaps the local tribes that used those paths didn't want to get involved for fear they would be accused of something nefarious.  There's so many unknowns.  I choose to believe one of them cleanly broke her ankle, the other either either stayed there and died with her, more likely than not by the smell of infection from the injury (hot and balmy climate) drew in predators (snakes, birds of prey, etc.), or the friend left to get help and got lost, eventually succumbing to the environment.  At least until something concrete to the contrary comes along; my opinion is always conditional upon the evidence at hand.
